Reorganization of the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mahmoud Abbas, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about a peace deal between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into America's Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the U.S. State Department, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What was achieved in Iraq - and what, above all, the Iraqi people can now achieve with the help of the Americans - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could provide for reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and the entire Middle East have taken effect.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the pre-planning by the Americans and the whole world, as well as the rapid, concentrated, and goal-oriented intervention of coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less severe than expected.
There is occasionally a need for humanitarian aid, but fortunately, the anticipated major crisis has not materialized.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. The supply of food, water, and medications is generally sufficient or improving at least.
The American government has provided approximately 600 million dollars through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian assistance.
Moreover, we must restore the basic order in Iraq.
Safety is an indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without safety, people cannot rebuild their country, return to work, or go back to school.
After the fall of Saddam, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness, and retribution.
Now it is top priority to put an end to this violence.
In addition, it is the task of international troops to ensure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors worsen the already fragile situation.
Long-term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures so they can ensure their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more as economic revival.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected, and modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of resources to process in Iraq.
The US provides more than 2 billion dollars for the support of initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production will be raised to a higher level.
Among the long-term challenges are increasing oil production and reducing Iraq's enormous debt.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographical, and political divides in Iraqi society, helping to renew politics in Iraq is likely the most challenging task.
Cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The American goal – an intact Iraq where laws are respected and a democratic government is established – is no pipe dream, especially not considering that Iraq has an educated population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is ready to continue on the path chosen and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have effects on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly any issue in foreign policy that more strongly engages and polarizes public opinion than the Palestinian question.
Nearly a year ago, President George W. Bush announced his goal of a democratic Palestinian state living in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the US developed a roadmap that brings us step by step closer to this goal.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be encouraged to set this process in motion and take measures to improve the situation before tackling more far-reaching issues at the negotiating table.
Finally, it cannot be allowed that terrorists undermine the peace process for all time.
But solving the Palestinian issue is not automatically the solution to all problems in the Middle East.
The challenges posed by Iran are clear and unequivocal. This country develops weapons of mass destruction and supports terrorism.
Such behavior mocks the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues this way, it will have consequences.
However, if Iran turns away from terror and the development of catastrophic weapons, the USA is ready to resume good relations with this country.
Just as the USA is willing to approach Syria if substantial attitude changes are achieved there.
A more general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
Too long did America tolerate the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to push for a representative form of government.
We have painfully come to realize that closed political systems can lead to resentments and extremism against the interests of the US, the West, and the entire world.
That is why we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Closed economic systems also pose a danger.
As indicated by last year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the development status of Arab countries), the Arab countries in the Middle East lagged far behind other regions in terms of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
For too long, these countries have watched economic boom pass them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If his recently expressed proposal for a free trade zone between the US and the Middle East within a decade were realized, it would be a sustainable basis for such development.
